Model architecture:

We used a half-width ResNet-18 style CNN trained from scratch. The model keeps
the main ResNet idea of residual blocks, where each block learns a correction
to the input representation and then adds the original shortcut connection back.
This helps gradient flow and lets us train a deeper CNN than a plain sequential
network.

The input to the model is an ImageNet-normalized tensor of shape [batch_size, 3,
224, 224]. The output is a logits tensor of shape [batch_size, 20].

Layer-by-layer structure:

1. Stem:
   Conv2d 3 -> 32 with kernel size 3 and padding 1, followed by BatchNorm2d and
   ReLU. 
   Shape: [B, 3, 224, 224] -> [B, 32, 224, 224].

2. Pool 1:
   MaxPool2d with kernel size 2 and stride 2. 
   Shape: [B, 32, 224, 224] -> [B, 32, 112, 112].

3. Stage 1:
   Two residual blocks with 32 channels. Each block contains two 3x3
   convolutions with BatchNorm and ReLU, plus a shortcut connection.
   Shape: [B, 32, 112, 112] -> [B, 32, 112, 112].

4. Pool 2:
   MaxPool2d reduces the feature map size again.
   Shape: [B, 32, 112, 112] -> [B, 32, 56, 56].

5. Stage 2:
   Two residual blocks. The first block increases the channel count from 32 to
   64 using a 1x1 convolution in the shortcut path, and the second block keeps
   64 channels.
   Shape: [B, 32, 56, 56] -> [B, 64, 56, 56].

6. Pool 3:
   MaxPool2d reduces spatial size.
   Shape: [B, 64, 56, 56] -> [B, 64, 28, 28].

7. Stage 3:
   Two residual blocks. The first block increases the channel count from 64 to
   128, and the second block keeps 128 channels.
   Shape: [B, 64, 28, 28] -> [B, 128, 28, 28].

8. Pool 4:
   MaxPool2d reduces spatial size.
   Shape: [B, 128, 28, 28] -> [B, 128, 14, 14].

9. Stage 4:
   Two residual blocks. The first block increases the channel count from 128 to
   256, and the second block keeps 256 channels.
   Shape: [B, 128, 14, 14] -> [B, 256, 14, 14].

10. Global average pooling:
    AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1, 1)) summarizes each of the 256 feature maps into one
    value. This creates a compact image representation before classification.
    Shape: [B, 256, 14, 14] -> [B, 256, 1, 1].

11. Classifier:
    The pooled tensor is flattened to [B, 256], then passed through Dropout
    with p=0.3 and a Linear layer from 256 features to 20 output logits.
    Shape: [B, 256] -> [B, 20].

Our model is a from-scratch convolutional image classifier for the 20-class
hackathon task. During development, we started with simpler CNN models and a
small number of epochs in order to verify that the full training, prediction,
and evaluation pipeline worked correctly. After that, we made the model more
complex while still using the same number of epochs, which at that point was
10. This led to underfitting: the model had more capacity, but did not train
long enough to use it well.

To address this, we increased the number of epochs and experimented with 30
epochs. This improved training performance, but we observed signs of
overfitting, where the training loss continued improving while validation
performance stopped improving or became less stable. We therefore chose a more
balanced setting of 17 epochs, aiming to give the model enough time to learn without fitting too strongly to the training data.

We ran the training experiments on Google Colab because the training process was
too heavy and unstable on our local computers. Using Colab allowed us to avoid
local crashes and improve iteration time while testing different model and
training configurations.

For the data split, we initially divided the original images in a balanced,
class-preserving way into 60% train, 20% validation, 10% test, and 10% other.
The "other" split was kept aside while we were still deciding how to use it.
Later, we decided to merge the "other" images into the training split, so the
final clean split used 70% for training, 20% for validation, and 10% for local
testing.

For robustness, we used image manipulations during training through the
"change_images_for_training.py" pipeline, which is not submitted. The training transform applies random in-memory augmentations such as random resized crop, horizontal flip, brightness/contrast/saturation/hue changes, random grayscale conversion, and small random rotations. These manipulations are meant to reduce the model's dependence on exact colors, lighting conditions, object placement, and small orientation changes.

We used different preprocessing for training and validation. Training uses
random transformations so that the same original image can appear slightly
different across epochs. Validation uses deterministic preprocessing with
resize, center crop, tensor conversion, and ImageNet normalization. This keeps
validation stable and makes validation accuracy comparable across epochs.

To save disk space, we did not save the randomly manipulated images as new image
files. Instead, the images are loaded from disk, transformed temporarily in
memory, converted into tensors, and passed to the network. After the batch is
processed, those manipulated versions are discarded. This allowed us to expose
the model to many visual variations without physically storing extra copies on
the computer.

We also evaluated performance separately on clean validation images and on
augmented validation images. This helped us monitor both standard
classification accuracy and robustness to visual manipulations.
